<section>
    <header>Combat Loop</header>
    <ol>
        <li>Determine if anyone has surprise</li>
        <li>Establish positions on the board</li>
        <li>Roll initiative (surprise ground goes in order)</li>
        <li>Take turns</li>
        <li>Begin next round (#4) until end of combat</li>
    </ol>
    <h2>Notes</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>it is not your turn, decide what you are going to do!</li>
        <li>Yes, something might happen before your turn when the monsters take their turn that will change what you want to do. 
            Generally, however, it is much more likely that what you had wanted to do is still what you’re going to do. (This is the best advice for tabletop games in general)</li>
        <li>Flavour is fun! But it shouldn’t slow combat. Know what your flavour is, and be prepared that, worst-case, it does nothing</li>
        <li>Your flavour must conform to the rules! We can stretch them, but not break them.</li>
        <li>Combat turns should take ~5-10 seconds per turn</li>
        <li>Turn limits are capped at 30 seconds per turn</li>
        <li>A round should take no more than 5 minutes!</li>
        <li>The longer your turns take, the more “RNJesus” affects you. A miss doesn’t matter as much if you’re only out for 1 minute, whereas if rounds take 20 minutes then the game gets boring for everyone.</li>
        <li>Try to avoid metagaming</li>
        <li>Inordinate tactical communication can be heard by the enemy :)</li>
        <li>You should know exactly what a spell does &amp; how it is used before you use it</li>
        <li>Monsters generally have a theme, strength, and weakness. Trying to figure this out is a good idea</li>
        <li>A round of combat, in game time, lasts 6 seconds</li>
        <li>Monsters follow the exact same set of rules that you do, with few exceptions</li>
        <li>Monsters will react to you and what you are doing. Use this to your advantage</li>
        <li>Always have your “AC” and “Passive Perception” numbers ready</li>
        <li>Always have your attack / spellcasting / damage dice numbers ready</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        Cover:
        <ul>
            <li>1/2 cover is +2 ac, dex throws</li>
            <li>3/4 cover: +5 ac, dex throws</li>
            <li>Total cover: cannot hit (melee or ranged), dex throws auto save</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Remembering the above allows me, the Dungeon Master, to play the game with you instead of being a rules engine. The shorter turns everyone takes, the more time we can allocate to cool things and epic protagonist moments.
    </p>
</section>
